support.p: A manuscript consisting of parchment leaves (Part 1) preceded by a fragment from an older manuscript that has been reused as an endleaf for this manuscript (Part 1)

foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos, by H.L. PinkPink, H. L..

f. [i] is a fragment from an older manuscript that has been reused as an endleaf for this manuscript; ff. 1-2 and ff. 169-170 originally served as flyleaves and are treated as such in the description of the manuscript's extent.

signatures.p: A modern hand has added crosses in pencil to the lower outer corners of the rectos of the innermost bifolia of quires.

supportDesc.condition: Fragile binding with deteriorated boards and broken spine. Tears in the parchment have been repaired with white thread (e.g. see the lower margin of ff. 43r, 58r, and 100r); there is a large tear in the margin of f. 28.

origin.note: Suggested by the added verse on f. 169r and spine label.

provenance.p: Francis John Henry Jenkinson (1853-1923) Jenkinson, Francis John Henry, 1853-1923, librarian of the University of Cambridge: bought from J. Westell Westell, J. . Name and note inscribed in pencil by Jenkinson on f. 2v: J. Westell Nov. 6 1885 and F. Jenkinson.

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library on 20 November 1893 by Francis John Henry Jenkinson (1853-1923), librarian of the University of Cambridge Jenkinson, Francis John Henry, 1853-1923: this date inscribed in pencil in the lower margin of f. 3r: Presented 1893.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on Jayne Ringrose, Summary Catalogue of the Additional Medieval Manuscripts in Cambridge University Library acquired before 1940 (Woodbridge, 2009), by kind permission of the Boydell Press; an unpublished description by C.E. Sayle Sayle, C.E. (Charles Edward), 1864-1924, now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/72; an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1926 and 1930 by M.R. James James, M.R. (Montague Rhodes), 1862-1936, now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/74); and an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1948 and 1970 by H.L. Pink Pink, H. L., now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/75).

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

msItem.title: Fragment of the Decretals of Gregory IX, Book I, Chapter IX
msItem.author: Pope Gregory IX
msItem.incipit: [i] verso [m]entio non habetur . Si eis [dolo] vel negligentia vti propo[suerit]
msItem.explicit: [i] recto [prio]res habere de quibus in p[osteriobius]
msItem.note: This is a fragment of a 13th-century manuscript copy that has been used as binding material for MS Add. 3120 (bound upside down).

support.p: A single fragment of a parchment leaf.

p.seg: Ruled in leadpoint, frame only, with occasional line ruling. Probably double columns (but this cannot be confired since the fragment does not show the full width of the leaf's original text space). 44 lines to the page, written below top line.

handNote.p: Copied by a single hand in a Gothic Textualis script.

origin.origDate: Copied in the 13th century (probably in the second half of the century).

signatures.p: Leaf signatures mostly cropped off, but still visible in the lower right-hand corners of the first halves of quires 14 (o-oooo), 15 (È-ÈÈÈ), 18 (the word 'aue' with a single horizontal line above it - the word aue with four horizontal lines above it), 19 (c-cccc), 20 (d-dddd), and 21 (f-ffff)

catchwords.seg: Catchwords in the lower right-hand corners of the last versos of quires.

layout.seg: Ruled in leadpoint, frame only and line ruling. Double colums. written below top line, 60 lines per page.

handNote.p: Written by a single hand in a Northern Textualis script.

decoNote.p: A dragon drawn in penwork of blue and red ink in the lower margin of f. 75r.
Full or partial 'J' borders in blue and red on ff. 3r, 3v, 19r, 31v, 32r, 42v, 43r, 58v, 75r, 87v, 121r, 131r, 131v.
Large puzzle initials (6-13 lines) in blue and red and penwork decoration in the same colours on ff. 3r, 3v, 19r, 31v, 32r, 42v [2x], 49v [2x], 75r [2x], 87v, 121r [2x], 131r, 131v, 144v.
Large initials (6-11 lines) outlined in blue filled with penwork decoration in red and blue that also surrounds the letters on 3r, 43r, 58v.
Smaller initials (2-3 lines) in blue or red with penwork decroation and pen-flourishing in the opposite colour throughout.
Titles and headings rubricated in red throughout.
A drawing of a hare in brown ink higlighted in yellow, illustrating a recipe including ingredients taken from the hare to remedy rabies caused by a dog's bite in the outer margin of f. 101r.
Paraphs in blue or red ink.
Run-over symbols decorated with human faces and hybrid figures in brown and red ink (e.g. ff. 111r and 168r).
Catchwords sometimes in frames of brown ink.

additions.p: The number 192 is written in an (?) 18th-century script in the lower margin of f. 3r, possibly representing a pressmark or lot number.
The number 27 is written on a loose paper slip inserted in the gutter between f. 91 and 92, perhaps representing an auction number.

origin.note: Suggested by the added verse on f. 169r and spine label.
